metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #418
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Code Page 437 // Ishihara #208
metadata.description:
In order to understand what you see before your eyes you must first open this artwork in both Firefox and any other web browser of your choice, at the same time, to experience it as intended.

A combination of ishihara palettes and cross-browser bugs are used to explore neurodiversity by forcing the viewer to take additional manual steps to see the world from a different perspective. A whole new understanding of colour blindness should unfold as you struggle through inaccessibility yourself.

The 640x400px canvas consists of 25 rows, with 80 columns per row for a total of 2000 letters, using only 16 glyphs from the Codepage 437 character set scaled to a resolution of 8x16 pixels per character.

Codepage 437 is the original IBM PC-ASCII font from August 1981, often referred to as the DOS font.

metadata.name: AutomatonII #19
metadata.description: Automaton I and Automaton II began life as the sleeve artwork for a concept LP about automata - self propelling machines, puppets and models that were once the heralds of a bright, technological future. Referencing retro-futurism, VHS idents and 70s pulp sci-fi covers, these generative pieces evoke mysterious, immersive spaces, using simple geometry and a random walking algorithm.

metadata.name: Clerestory #316
metadata.description:
Windows welcome daylight, admit fresh air, and offer a view into the outside world. They rarely shatter, always confess the passage of time, and sometimes allow others a chance to look in.

What would the space you're in feel like if it had no windows?

'Clerestory' is an abstract exploration of stained glass windows, drafting shattered sketches for ten potential locations from various perspectives and moments in time. 

Made with WebGL, p5.js, and <3 | CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Plottable Storm #82
metadata.description:
Plottable Storm is a flow field simulating fountain pen ink drawing on paper on its digital form. 10 inks, many rarity features varying noise, size and color positioning. Having only one color is rare.
The digital NFTs can be used to perform a physical action: @greweb plotting on demand a fountain pen plot for those who also want physical originals. Full article: https://greweb.me/2021/11/plottable-storm

Digital and Physical art, hybrid and decoupled:
- The art is made as a regular digital NFT on Tezos blockchain – its digital form rendered with WebGL shaders.
- Token to the physical world: owning each NFT confer the power to request the related physical plot – See https://greweb.me/plots/nft

Tip: right click or Drag&Drop the canvas will get you the plottable SVG.

@greweb – 2021 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Eikonal identities #134
metadata.description:
Works in the invisible
Inevitable shadows
Digital exorcism
Silicon catharsis


Eikonal
- Usually "eikonal equation" : the wave-like description of the propagation of light through a medium
- In optics, relative to the formation of an image
- anagram : e-kaolin



-----
* What/How *

Product of the code.

A picture generated by a succession of chaotic events applied to a system of 4.2 million particles.
The drawing process consists of mixing and projecting the particles randomly in space.

Each image is unique and depends only on the address of minter's wallet and current iteration number.

-----
* Technics *

- Hand written code in Javascript, GLSL
- Uses three.js library, WebGL particles, physics
- Generates a FullHD PNG (1080x1080 px bitmap 24bits)
- Takes less than 15 seconds of generation on a relatively recent GPU (>2017)

-----

metadata.name: Textile Bacteria #212
metadata.description:
Telar's code became self-aware and tried to escape. I built a containment unit. "Textile Bacteria" is the result.

--

The piece is based on the 1970's work of the British mathematician John Conway's "Conway's Game of Life" cellular automaton. To avoid bacteria from dying when one of the threads ends up entirely on top of the other the algorithm adds one pseudorandom artificial cross in the weaving feeding the creatures keeping at the same time the weave consistent.

- Left-click to feed dead bacteria.
- Use the arrow keys to flip between the face and the back of the fabric.
- Press 'SPACE' on your keyboard to pause/play. 
- Press 'ENTER' on your keyboard to rewind. 
- Press 'F' on your keyboard to toggle between full-screen and regular view. 
- Press 'S' on your keyboard to save it as a 36 megapixels print.

metadata.name: Ries #389
metadata.description:
Ries is 500 sheets of paper. 
Ries is an cut-up text-artwork.
Ries is artwork generated by an algorithm based on seeded random numbers.
Ries is a digital artwork installed in 5 forms in exhibitions setting.
Ries is an NFT artwork. 

Ries is an artwork where I try bring together my experience of doing gallery exhibitions, my love for generative and copy machine art, DIY-punk aesthetics, NFT’s and chaos. 

The edition of Ries will be installed in different forms and collages in a gallery exhibition in Walden Kunstaustellungen in Berlin in July of 2022. Opening is at 8.7. 19.00, welcome if you are in Berlin.
/www.galerie-walden.de/

The seed idea for the project was the method of cut-up where a text (or something else) is cut into pieces and then rearranged to form something new. A modified Markov’s Chain algorithm makes a small text or a group of words from a pool of texts that include Art texts about cut up technique and generative art talk from tweets. These words form a visual bottom layer and then another layer of words samples the first, cutting it up and thus following the theme of the artwork.

Since the single iterations of the project are designed to be used in a collage, they come in various tone, density, detail and scale. One can test from the variations button and get a sense of what the generator produces. 

Controls in live view:
-Pressing  j exports the current image as jpeg
-Pressing  p  exports the current image as png

To change the detail level one can access the pixel density of render by adding ?pixDens=4 to the end of the URL in live view. You can of course you any number other than 4 also. I it renders just a black image, you have to lower the number, since it is then too large for WEBGL to render.

Designed to be best rendered on desktop Chrome.

Pricing info
22 tez - Includes a gallery shown, signed print sent to minter by mail or by telefax(!)
11 tez - A fair price for an artwork, also the minter can personally pick up a signed gallery shown print from the gallery, after the exhibition.
5 tez - 1/2 fair price
2 tez - bottom dollar

If you minted on lower tiers and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm to “upgrade”. If you bought secondary, and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm.

Features exist mostly to help with artwork pairing for the collectors.


Markov’s chain code core is based on Markov Me! By https://codepen.io/alexkramerbanjo , MIT License

Displacement shader based on the wonderful shader examples by Adam Ferris


The artist holds the right to use the whole edition of Ries for display purposes for future exhibitions without asking permission or notifying the owners of the NFT’s.

metadata.name: Ganymede #38
metadata.description:
Ganymede is the largest moon in the Solar System, and nearly as large as the Earth. Its surface exhibits many fine cracks and fissures, thought to be caused by tidal heating due to the influence of nearby Jupiter. But, on closer inspection, one may see the effects of life on the surface patterning. In this animation, we see first an initial outward wave of activity, followed by a period of vigorous bubbling of interactive competition, and then finally intelligent structuring of the surface, leaving behind arcane symbols etched in the ice.

Programmed with vanilla javascript and the FastNoiseLite package.

Press "s" to save the image as a png file.
